# Localization

The addon ships its own lightweight locale system. **No Ace3 / AceLocale.**

## Files

- `Modules/Locale.lua` — registry, metatable fallback, `Activate`, `RunCallbacks`,
  alias support. Loads first (before any locale data and any UI).
- `Locales/enUS.lua` — required base. Every key the addon uses MUST exist here.
  All other locales fall back to this one.
- `Locales/esES.lua` — Spanish (Spain).
- `Locales/esMX.lua` — alias of `esES` via `ns.Locale:RegisterAlias`.

Add a new locale by creating `Locales/<code>.lua` and registering it in the
TOC right after the existing locales.

## Runtime contract

- Strings are accessed through `ns.L.SOME_KEY` (or `ns.L["SOME_KEY"]`).
- `ns.L` has a metatable that returns the key itself if the string is missing,
  so the UI never crashes — it just shows the raw key, which makes missing
  translations visible.
- `ns.Locale:Activate()` must run inside `ADDON_LOADED` for the addon, AFTER
  `ns.Database:Initialize()` (so `GCM_Settings.locale` is available) and
  BEFORE `ns.Database:ApplyDefaultSchedules()` (so default schedules pick up
  the active locale).
- Modules with UI text register a callback via
  `ns.Locale:RegisterCallback(fn)` to (re)apply localized strings. Callbacks
  run after `Activate` and again after `/gcmlang` switches the language at
  runtime.

## Coding rules

- **Never** hardcode user-facing strings inside Lua modules. Always go through
  `ns.L.<KEY>`.
- Keys are SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE, English, descriptive (`SCHEDULE_UPDATED`, not
  `MSG1`).
- `string.format` placeholders go inside the locale value. Document the order
  of arguments via the key name when ambiguous (e.g. `LABEL_CORE_ROW = "%s Core %d:"`).
- Color codes (`|cffXXXXXX...|r`) belong in the locale value when they carry
  branding (e.g. `BRAND`, `BRAND_GREEN`). Addon release version comes from the
  TOC (`## Version`) via `ns.addonVersion` set in `Core.lua` on load; localized
  login lines use a `%s` placeholder, e.g.
  `print(ns.L.BRAND .. " " .. string.format(ns.L.LOGIN_READY, ns.addonVersion or "?"))`.
- The `Locales/*.lua` files are the **only** Lua files allowed to contain
  non-English text. Everything else (variable names, function names, keys,
  log keys) stays in English.

## Adding a new string

1. Add the key to `Locales/enUS.lua` with the English value.
2. Add the same key to every other locale file with its translation. Missing
   keys fall back to enUS automatically; aliases (e.g. esMX → esES) inherit
   for free.
3. Reference it from code as `ns.L.YOUR_KEY`.

## Switching language

- Auto: `GetLocale()` is read on `Activate`.
- Manual: `/gcmlang <code>` sets `GCM_Settings.locale` and re-runs callbacks.
- Reset: `/gcmlang reset` clears the override.
- A `/reload` is recommended after switching to fully refresh frame text that
  may not be wired to a callback yet.
